04449nam a22005895i 9780889208780DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20061995xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892087807 a10.51644/97808892087802doi  a(DE-B1597)667421  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBQ7235bB64 1995eb 7aREL0070402bisacsh04a294.3/911 aBoisvert, Mathieu, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Five Aggregates :bUnderstanding Theravada Psychology and Soteriology /cMathieu Boisvert. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (184 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEditions SR ;v1700tFront Matter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Tables -- tAcknowledgements -- tForeword -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tThe Concept of Khandha -- tThe Rūpakkhandha -- tThe Vedanākkhandha -- tThe Saññākkhandha -- tThe Sañkhārakkhandha -- tThe Viññānakkhandha -- tInterrelation of the Aggregates -- tConclusion -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tSeries Published by Wilfrid Laurier University Press for the Canadian Corporation for Studies in Religion/ Corporation Canadienne des Sciences Religieuses0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIf Buddhism denies a permanent self, how does it perceive identity? According to Buddhist texts, the entire universe, including the individual, is made up of different phenomena, which Buddhism classifies into different categories: what we conventionally call a “person” can be understood in terms of five aggregates, the sum of which must not be taken for a permanent entity, since beings are nothing but an amalgam of ever-changing phenomena. Although the aggregates are only a “convenient fiction,” the Buddha nevertheless made frequent use of the aggregate scheme when asked to explain the elements at work in the individual. In this study Mathieu Boisvert presents a detailed analysis of the five aggregates (pañcakkhandhā) and establishes how the Theravda tradition views their interaction. He clarifies the fundamentals of Buddhist psychology by providing a rigorous examination of the nature and interrelation of each of the aggregates and by establishing, for the first time, how the function of each of these aggregates chains beings to the cycle of birth, death and rebirth — the theory of dependent origination (paticcasamuppāda). Boisvert contends that without a thorough understanding of the five aggregates, we cannot grasp the liberation process at work within the individual, who is, after all, simply an amalgam of the five aggregates. The Five Aggregates represents an important and original contribution to Buddhist studies and will be of great interest to all scholars and students of Buddhism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSalvationxBuddhism. 0aSkandhas. 0aTheravāda BuddhismxDoctrines. 0aTheravāda BuddhismxPsychology. 0aTheravāda BuddhismxDoctrines. 0aTheravāda BuddhismxPsychology. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / Theravada.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920878040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889208780423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889208780/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles